<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>weissblau</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Heyokah<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2001<br />
	Location: Halas
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I find it REALLY hard to believe that pinging the local loopback address (127.0.0.1) will have any effect whatsoever on the game.  The loopback address is optimized in the network stack so that no data ever goes out on the wire.<br />
<br />
I can believe, maybe, that pinging some external address might have an effect, but it's far-fetched since plenty of network traffic is taking place just on your Everquest connection.<br />
<br />
You can get more sophisticated ping utilities that allow you to select the time between pings, btw, which would help your bandwidth a lot more than reducing the payload size.  I use PingPlotter, it's very nice shareware and graphically shows the ping delay to ALL the intermediate steps in the route to your destination.  <a href="http://www.pingplotter.com" target="_blank">http://www.pingplotter.com</a> .</p>
	
	
	
